text.tspan: Proposal: Timeline view optimised for transition editing
Observation: With short transitions and long clips in-between, the workflow is usually zoom in to the transition,
edit or add it, zoom out, pan to the next transition, zoom in again, and so on.
With a transition duration of 5 frames and a clip length of 30 s = 900 frames, transitions are tiny on the timeline.
The proposed view divides clips into parts of fixed screen width, independant of the actual frame length. The above timeline
A new block is started when a transition starts or ends, and when a clip starts or ends.
This view is much more compact for this task. It obviously is not suited for all tasks, but it does not need to be; that is what the “normal” timeline view is for.
Frame numbers (like 5 f) denote the transition’s length and can be changed there.
Computing the view can be accomplished with a simple scanline algorithm. We parse all clips and transitions from left to right
and add a box border for each start and end of an item.
